5. STRUCTURAL AND THERMAL DESIGN

5.1 Track Support Structure

The 3.2 km track is supported by 641 composite piers at 5-meter intervals:

Pier Design:

· Material: Carbon-fiber/epoxy composite
· Height: 2-5 m (following terrain)
· Cross-section: Hexagonal, 0.5 m diameter
· Compressive strength: 1,500 MPa
· Thermal expansion coefficient: -0.7 × 10⁻⁶/K

Foundation Design:

· Microwave-sintered regolith pad: 2 m × 2 m × 0.5 m
· Bearing pressure: <100 kPa
· Settlement tolerance: <1 mm over 30 years

5.2 Thermal Management System

The lunar thermal environment ranges from 40 K (shadow) to 400 K (sun). The system maintains 77 K for HTS and 4.2 K for SMES:

Heat Load Analysis:

Source Power (W) Management Strategy
Ohmic losses (launch) 10⁶ peak Phase-change material buffer
Solar radiation 1,350 W/m² Multi-layer insulation (MLI)
Infrared emission 300 W/m² Low-emissivity coatings
Conduction through supports 100 total Fiberglass composite thermal breaks

Cryogenic Cooling:

· Primary refrigerator: 4-stage Stirling cycle
· Cooling power: 200 W at 4.2 K + 2 kW at 77 K
· Working fluid: Helium-4
· Radiator area: 500 m² at 300 K

5.3 Regolith Shielding Architecture

The entire track is buried under 5 meters of regolith for thermal, radiation, and micrometeorite protection:

Shielding Effectiveness:

· Thermal swing reduction: 400 K → ±5 K
· Radiation dose reduction: 1000× (from 380 mSv/year to <0.4 mSv/year)
· Micrometeorite protection: Handles impacts up to 1 cm diameter at 20 km/s

Construction Sequence:

1. Excavate trench: 4 m deep × 6 m wide
2. Install track and cryogenic systems
3. Backfill with graded regolith (0.1-10 mm particles)
4. Compact using vibratory plates
5. Add 1-meter sacrificial layer on top

---

6. PAYLOAD AND SLED DESIGN

6.1 Sled ("Buckbot") Specifications

The sled is a reusable electromagnetic interface that carries the payload:

Dimensions: 3.0 m long × 1.5 m wide × 0.8 m tall
Mass: 2,000 kg (including magnets and structure)
Maximum acceleration: 150g design limit
Operational lifetime: 10,000 cycles

Key Subsystems:

1. Halbach array: 20 neodymium magnet modules
2. Superconducting coils: 20 REBCO coils, 5 MJ each
3. Structural frame: Carbon-silicon carbide composite
4. Guidance skids: Tungsten-carbide wear surfaces
5. Telemetry package: Fiber-optic sensors throughout

6.2 Payload Container Standardization

The "Space Brick" container standard enables automated handling:

External Dimensions: 2.5 m × 1.0 m × 1.0 m
Mass Limits: 500-1,000 kg
Interface: ISO 668-compatible corner castings
Internal Environment: Temperature-controlled (200-300 K), vibration-damped

Acceleration Survival Design:

· All components potted in low-density polyurethane foam
· Circuit boards aligned parallel to acceleration vector
· No moving parts >1 g mass
· Fluid systems use surface tension management

6.3 Sled Recovery System

After payload release, the sled is decelerated and returned:

Deceleration Track: 500-meter regenerative braking section
Energy Recovery: 80% of sled kinetic energy returned to SMES
Return Loop: 3 km underground tunnel at 1 m/s
Cycle Time: 45 minutes total (launch to ready)

